<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I was going to answer you point by point but then I realized that three of the questions were identical.  When you chose a warrior you made a choice, you sacrificed solo ability for desirability in groups.  Everquest has classes that solo well, if you chose a class that does not, than the fault lies with your choice. A good group can easily equal or exceed the exp gain of solo play.   If every group you are in sucks, then I suggest you try to determine what all of those groups have in common that makes them suck.   There are lots of games on the market, Everquest just happens to be one of the few that requires interaction to succeed (though some classes are exceptions to this).   Part of the way that Verant has "encouraged" grouping is to place limitations on classes that makes them seek out other classes to compensate for those weaknesses.  <P>You hear all of the time from people that the main reason they continue to play is the friends that they have made.   By making people group, Verant forces people to meet others and develop friendships.  This more than any other facet of the game results in long term subscriptions.   Since Verant does not charge for time online, but rather charges a monthly subscription, there is really no advantage to Verant to have people play a large number of hours each month.  Those people actually use more resources per dollar and are less profitable for Verant.
</FONT>
